b'' b'someone sent me this faq by e-mail and i post my response here.' b'' b"[i'm not enforcing the inclusion limits on this faq because most" b"of our readers probably haven't seen it. --clh]" b'' b'christ warns that anyone who "breaks one of the least of these' b'commandments *and* teaches otheres to do the same will be called least in' b'the kingdom of heaven" (matt. this faq is so full of error that i' b'must respond to it. i hope that whoever maintains will remove from it the' b'partisan theology.' b'' b'| brothers and sisters,' b'| b"| being new to the faith and examining the decalogue closely, i've noticed the" b'| fourth commandment is pretty specific about "keeping the sabbath day." it' b'| states the 7th day( saturday is the sabbath while most christian religions' b"| keep( or atleast go to church on sunday. what's up?" b'|' b'| this is a frequently asked question. every time it arises, it causes' b'| months of debate. so let me see if i can answer you directly.' b"| basically it's because the law was given to moses as part of a" b"| specific covenanent with the jews. most of us aren't jews, so we" b"| aren't part of that covenant. there was an argument early in" b'| christian history about whether the mosaic laws should apply to' b'| gentiles who became christians. you can see the account of this' b'| debate in acts the main question there was circumcision, but' b'| keeping the sabbath would be part of it as well. the apostles' b'| concluded that we need not become jews in order to become christians,' b'| and therefore that rules such as circumcision did not apply to us.' b'' b'1. the law was known to man before it was revealed on mount sinai. rom' b'4:15 notes that "where no law is, there is no transgression." not only' b'did sin exist before sinai (eden), but the sabbath was kept before it' b'was revealed on sinai (ex b'' b'2. the problem with the first covenant was not the law, but the promise' b'which undergirded it. god wanted to perform his will in the lives of the' b'people, but in their ignorance after years of slavery, they promised' b'"what ever he says to do we will do." that is why the new covenant is' b'based on "better promises" (heb. rather than do away with the law' b'god promised to "put my laws in their minds and write them on their' b'hearts" (heb. b'' b'3. including the sabbath in the acts is selective inclusion. the' b'sabbath was more important to the jews than circumcision. if any attempt' b'had been made to do away with the sabbath the reaction would have been' b'even more strident than is recorded in acts do not confuse the weekly' b'sabbath of the decalogue with the ceremonial sabbaths which could occur at' b'any time of the week and were part of the law (ceremonial) which was' b'*added* because of transgression (of the moral law) (gal b'' b"4. israel stands for god's people of all time. that is why god *grafted*" b'the gentiles in. roma says that the adoption, the glory, the' b'covenants, the giving of the law, the service of god and the promises' b'belong to israelites. in explanation paul makes it clear that being born' b'into israel is not enough "for they are not all israel, which are of' b'israel" v then in gal he says "if ye be christ\'s, then are ye' b'abraham\'s seed, and heirs according to the promise." all christians are' b"abraham's seed, jews, israelites. not physically, for that is not the" b'criterion, but spiritually. we are joint heirs with jesus based on the' b'promise god made to all his people the israelites.' b'' b'|' b'| while christians agree that the ot laws do not all apply to us,' b'| because some of them are part of a specific covenanent with the jews,' b'| we also expect to see some similarity between the things god expected' b"| from the jews and the things he expects from us. after all, it's the" b'| same god. however there are several ways of dealing with this.' b'|' b'| these days the most common approach is to separate the ot commandments' b'| into "moral" and "ceremonial". ceremonial commandments apply only to' b'| the jews. they are part of the specific mosaic covenant. these are' b'| thinsg like the kosher laws and circumcision. moral laws apply to' b'| everyone. most of the commands are part of the moral law, except' b'| for the commandment about the sabbath. i believe most people who take' b'| this approach would say that the specific requirement to worship on' b'| the sabbath is part of the ceremonial law, but a general obligation to' b'| worship regularly is part of the general moral law. thus christians' b'| are free to choose the specific time we worship.' b'' b'people would probably agree but they are wrong. how can the sabbath' b'commandment be ceremonial when it is part of a law which predates the' b'ceremonial laws? you are not free to choose your time of worship. even' b'if you were why do you follow a day of worship which has its origins in pagan' b'sun worship. would you rather give up a day which god blessed,' b'sanctified, and hallowed in exchange for one which all church leaders' b'agree has not biblical foundation (see sabbath admissions in' b'soc.religion.christian.bible-study).' b'|' b'| a more radical approach (which is generally connected with john calvin' b'| and the reformed tradition) says that the law as a whole is no longer' b'| binding. instead, we are entirely under grace, and our behavior' b'| should be guided solely by love. portions of the ot law are still' b'| useful as guidance. but they are not properly speaking legally' b'| binding on us. in practice most people who take this position do not' b'| believe it is safe to leave christians without moral guidannce. while' b"| we may no longer be under law, as sinners, it's not safe for us to go" b"| into situations with no principles to guide us. we're too good at" b'| self-justification for that to be safe. thus christians do have moral' b"| guidance, from things like jesus' teachings, paul's advice, etc." b'| these may not be precisely a law, but they serve much the same' b'| function as, and have largely the same content as, the "moral law" in' b'| the previous analysis. while calvin would deny that we have a fixed' b'| legal responsibility to worship on any specific day, he would say that' b'| given human weakness, the discipline of regular worship is important.' b'|' b'i do not care what calvin or any theologian says. my guide is what god' b'says. if being not under the law means we do not have to keep the law,' b'why is it that the only section of the law we have trouble with is the' b'sabbath commandment, which is the only one god thought was important' b'enough to say *remember*? if you study the word deeply you will note that' b'the message is that we are no longer under the condemnation of the law but' b'freed by the grace of god. if a cop pulls me over for speeding, then in' b'court i ask for mercy and the judge does not throw the book at me but gives me' b'grace, do i walk out of the court saying "i can now go on speeding, for i' b'am now under grace?" being under grace i now drive within the speed' b'limit. paul adds to it in rom. "di we then make void the law through' b'faith? god forbid: yea, we establish the law." "wherefore the law is' b'holy, and the commandment holy, and just, and good" (rom. b'' b'| in both analyses, the specific day is not an issue. as a matter of' b"| tradition, we worship on sunday as a memorial of christ's" b"| resurrection. there's some debate about what acts shows about early" b'| christian worship. the most common analysis is that is shows jewish' b'| christians continuing to go to jewish services on the sabbath, but' b'| that specifically christian service were not necessarily held then.' b'| act shows worship on the first day (sunday), and i cor also' b'| implies gatherings on that day.' b'|' b'| there are a few groups that continue to believe christians have to' b'| worship on the sabbath (saturday). the best-known are the seventh-day' b"| adventists a