es christians as participating both in jewish temple' b'worship and in christian communion services in homes. obviously the' b'temple worship is on the sabbath. acts is an example of' b"christians participating in them. unfortunately it doesn't tell us" b"what day christians met in their houses. acts despite darius'" b'confusion, is described by acts as occuring on sunday. (i see no' b'reason to impose modern definitions of when days start, when the' b'biblical text is clear about what was meant.) the wording implies to' b"me that this was a normal meeting. it doesn't say they gathered to" b'see paul off, but that when they were gathered for breaking bread,' b"paul talked about his upcoming travel. but that's just not explicit" b'enough to be really convincing. similarly with cor it says' b"that on the first day they should set aside money for paul's" b'collection. now if you want to believe that they gathered specially' b"to do this, or that they did it in their homes, i can't disprove it," b'but the obvious time for a congregation to take an offering would be' b'when they normally gather for worship, and if they were expected to do' b'it in their homes there would be no reason to mention a specific day.' b'so i think the most obvious reading of this is that "on the first day' b'of every week" simply means every time they gather for worship.' b'' b'i think the reason we have only implications and not clear statements' b'is that the nt authors assumed that their readers knew when christian' b'worship was.' b'' b'--clh]' 